Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

Question 1: Most and Least Expensive Neighborhoods¶

In order to analyze which neighborhoods are the most and least expensive in San Francisco, I used the median of the Median Sold Price per Square Foot variable in the data from Zillow. I queried this database to get the columns MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes and RegionName. I turned this information into a data frame grouped by RegionName. I then made a bar graph using seaborn of the top 5 most expensive zip code regions, by median of the median sold price per square foot. The least expensive region was Hunters Point, as one might guess, at just under 300 dollars per square foot. The most expensive region was the portion of the Financial District along Market Street, at nearly 1400 dollars per square foot. This region was significantly more expensive than the next most expensive area, which was the South of Market along the Embarcadero, at a median of 800 dollars per square foot.

This is the most appropriate measure for determining how expensive a neighborhood is because the median of the median sold price per square foot controls for outliers, size of the house, and cost.

ByZip = ByZip.sort("MedianPrice")

Question 2: Most Dangerous Areas and Times in SF¶

First I plotted a bar graph of the number of reported crimes in each police district to get a sense of which neighborhoods have the most criminal activity. I found that the Southern police district has the highest number of reported crimes at nearly 200,000 reports.

I also made a bar graph of crime report counts across the days of the week to see if crime varies over the week. I found that Friday has the highest overall number of reported crimes at 160,000. I plotted a few of the most common crimes across the hour of the day and found that most crimes hit their low points at 5am, and high point at around 8pm. I plotted vandalism, robbery, assault, and vehicle theft, and found them to vary similarly throughout the day. A graph of these four crime rates showed that their numbers don't vary from month to month, except small spikes in October and in January, possibly from Halloween and New Year's festivities.

This evidence concludes that if you are in the Southern police district on a Friday between the hours of 8pm and 2am in October, you are likely in San Francisco's most dangerous time and place.

Question 3: Do Food Trucks Venture into High Crime Neighborhoods?¶

To answer this question I mapped the locations of all food truck permit holders around San Francisco. To avoid redundancy and to make the graph more legible, I narrowed the data down by choosing the most "typical" time frame for crimes - only crimes in July, 2015. I picked the month of July because it appears to be a near-average month for assaults in San Francisco. I also filtered out to include only Larceny/theft crime because as we will see in question 5, this is the most common crime in police districts.

I found that food trucks do seem to venture into neighborhoods that have higher levels of assault, especially in the Downtwon/Financial District area. One interesting divide I can see from these maps is Market Street: South of Market has slightly less assaults, and many more food trucks, while North of Market seems to have a few less food trucks and higher concentration of assault.

def draw_SF(figsize = [10,10],dpi=80):
    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize = figsize, dpi = dpi)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    
    bmap = Basemap(
        projection='lcc',
        lon_0=-122.4194,
        lat_0=37.7749,
        # in meters 
        width=25000,
        height=25000
    )

    bmap.drawcoastlines()
    bmap.drawcounties()
    bmap.readshapefile('./SF Find Neighborhoods/geo_export_c9b3feed-c93d-4ce7-acec-c6a649aa9cd2', 'cityCounties')
    return ax, fig, bmap

Question 4: Do food trucks correspond to increased noise violations?¶

For this question I plotted noise violations and food trucks on the map of San Francisco. At a glance, I do not see any patterns that would relate food trucks with noise violations. It looked like marked street and the Mission district had a strong clustering of both noise violations and food trucks. However, these noise violations contained so many different types of noises, such as construction and traffic sounds, that I wanted to subset the data to get a more accurate picture.

I decided to subset this to the noise types I thought would most likely be correlated with food trucks - major event, entertainment, mechanical noise, and other excessive noise. I plotted these noise violations against food trucks on a second map graph and found that Market and Mission streets definitely show a strong concentration of both food trucks and potentially food truck related noise violations.

Question 5: How Does Crime Change Across Police Districts?¶

Here I made pie charts of the types of crimes occurring in the highest and lowest crime police districts. I used the bar charts from question 2 to determine that the Richmond District has the lowest number of reported crimes, and the Southern district has the highest.

The first pie chart is of the Richmond district, and shows that the top three most commonly reported crimes are larceny/theft, non-criminal, and other offenses. These crimes are also the top three most common in the Southern police district. Assault and vandalism also take similar rankings. However, warrants are not among the most crimes in the Richmond District, but they are 5th most common in the Southern district. We also see drug related offenses to be more common in the Southern district, and Vehicle theft more common in the Richmond. In both cases, I was surprised to see how prevalent missing persons reports are.
